Growing up an only child:  I never really realized my childhood was different because it is all I ever knew.  I got really good about making up my own little world and stories.  I always had my nose in a book.  I  also played well with other kids when we traveled the world, because I usually look different than the community so people were fascinated by me.  I did have a hard time socializing with my peers in the UK.  Once I settled into university things got easier.  Sorry for the long text message!

So the end of the relationship and the loss of my son was also what promoted me for the move to Canada. I needed a change of city, region, country, and continent.  You asked what made me move here, but itâs long story that is personal.  I came here to heal and try to pick the pieces.

My delivery date was right in December.  We planned on having a simple ceremony to be marred before the due date.  My water broke unexpectedly in later September of 2019.  My son was born premature at 28 weeks and we named him Oliver. He was very tiny and he passed away right before Christmas 2019 (just happened).  He survived strongly for 2.5 months but he had so many health issues and...

During this difficult time with Oliver in the hospital fighting for his life. I stopped working and was by his side daily.  My ex turned to drugs, drinking, and sex (lots with other women).  I did not learn about all the other woman until after in January.  Christmas was horrible and when I found out about the other woman. I packed up all my stuff from our London flat and went home to Scotland.

Long story shortened: I was with my ex boyfriend who I was in a long term relationship of 4 years and I became pregnant in March of 2019. It was unplanned but we were both very excited.

My ex was a rock musician and his hours were totally different than mine.  So we were trying to figure out life with a baby and our careers.  Everything went well, we rented a nice size flat in Chelsea and started settling in for our family.

âª Built on an island a mile away from the Village of Dornie, the land was first occupied in 634 AD, home to the monastic cell of Bishop Donan. During the 13th century, Alexander II built the first incarnation of Eilean Donan to defend the surrounding mountains of Kintail and the Isle of Skye against the Viking hordes. This original castle is said to have an immense curtained wall connecting seven towers and spanning the entire island. Come 1719, a lesser-known Jacobite uprising partially destroyed the structure, and for the following 200 years, it lay in near ruins. Finally, in 1911, Colonel John MacRae-Gilstrap arrived. He bought the island and restored the castle, reopening it in 1932.â£

Hadrianâs Wall marked the boundary between Roman Britannia and unconquered Caledonia to the north. The wall lies entirely within England and has never formed the Anglo-Scottish border. The largest Roman archaeological feature in Britain, it runs a total of 73 miles (117.5 kilometres) in northern England. Regarded as a British cultural icon, Hadrian's Wall is one of Britain's major ancient tourist attractions. It was designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1987. In comparison, the Antonine Wall, thought by some to be based on Hadrian's wall (the Gillam hypothesis), was not declared a World Heritage site until 2008.
